<page_title>Light can heat matter</page_title>
<text>  Light can heat matter
p. 6 of 8
&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

How does light energy convert into heat energy? When a photon is absorbed by an electron, the electron will be excited to a higher energy level. The higher energy level is usually unstable, hence the electron will stay there for only a short while and fall into a lower level if it receives no more energy. When it falls to a lower level, two things can happen. 

1) It can emit a photon. This can carry some or all of the energy in the excited state in the form of light. 

or

2) It can transfer the energy of the excited state into the kinetic energy, causing an increase in temperature. This is called radiationless transition (because no photon was emitted).  The probability of raditionless transition depends on the physical properties of materials.

Consider the model below.  Unlike the other models we&apos;ve run, this time we&apos;ll shade each atom based on its kinetic energy.  That is, an unshaded atom (the way they look now, before running the model) represents low kinetic energy.  An atom of higher kinetic energy will become shaded in red (see the scale in the upper left hand corner of simulator box).  In the upper right hand corner of the simulator box we have a device which will record the temperature increase.

Click Run to activate the white light source.  Let the model run for two to three minutes.  Experiment with adjusting the intensity of the light source and the simulation speed.  While the model is running answer the question below.


  
  


 

